{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "A pathogen breaches your skin or slips past mucus membranes. The moment it enters, it's like an alarm tripping — nearby cells detect foreign molecular patterns and start signaling danger.",
      "title": "Breach Detected"
    },
    {
      "text": "Damaged cells release chemical distress signals called cytokines. These spread outward like smoke signals, alerting nearby immune cells: \"Intruder here! Send backup!\"",
      "title": "The Alarm Spreads"
    },
    {
      "text": "Blood vessels near the breach widen and become leaky. This is inflammation — it floods the area with fluid and creates an entry point for immune cells to rush in.",
      "title": "Blood Vessels Open the Gates"
    },
    {
      "text": "Neutrophils arrive first, racing toward the chemical signals like firefighters following smoke. They're fast but blunt — engulfing and destroying anything that looks foreign.",
      "title": "First Responders Arrive"
    },
    {
      "text": "Macrophages move in next, swallowing pathogens whole. But here's the key move: they chop up the invader and display pieces on their surface like wanted posters.",
      "title": "Macrophages Sound the Alert"
    },
    {
      "text": "These pathogen fragments travel to lymph nodes where helper T cells examine them. When a T cell's receptor matches the fragment perfectly, it's like finding the right key for a lock.",
      "title": "T Cells Get the Intel"
    },
    {
      "text": "The activated helper T cell begins dividing rapidly, creating an army of clones. It also releases signals that wake up B cells carrying matching antibody blueprints.",
      "title": "The Cloning Begins"
    },
    {
      "text": "B cells transform into antibody factories, pumping out millions of Y-shaped proteins. These flood the bloodstream, hunting for pathogens with matching shapes to latch onto.",
      "title": "Antibody Production Ramps Up"
    },
    {
      "text": "Antibodies stick to pathogens, neutralizing them and flagging them for destruction. It's like painting targets — other immune cells now know exactly what to attack.",
      "title": "Tagging the Enemy"
    },
    {
      "text": "Killer T cells hunt down infected body cells — cells that have been hijacked by viruses. They force these compromised cells to self-destruct before the virus can spread.",
      "title": "Killer T Cells Clean House"
    },
    {
      "text": "As pathogens are eliminated, suppressor signals gradually calm the immune response. Inflammation subsides, and the battlefield returns to normal tissue.",
      "title": "The All-Clear Signal"
    },
    {
      "text": "Most immune cells die off, but some B and T cells transform into memory cells. They'll patrol quietly for decades, ready to trigger an instant, overwhelming response if this pathogen ever returns.",
      "title": "Veterans Stand Down"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Picture the DNA double helix twisted tightly, like a zipper closed shut. Before transcription can begin, the helix must unwind at a specific spot — the promoter region. Enzymes begin loosening the coils, preparing the stage for the main event.",
      "title": "The Helix Begins to Unwind"
    },
    {
      "text": "RNA polymerase arrives at the promoter sequence like a train pulling into a station. It recognizes the 'start here' signal and locks onto the DNA. This binding triggers the final separation of the two DNA strands — the template is now exposed.",
      "title": "RNA Polymerase Docks In"
    },
    {
      "text": "With the strands separated, RNA polymerase reads the first DNA base. It grabs a matching RNA nucleotide from the surrounding soup of free-floating molecules. A pairs with U, G pairs with C. The first link of the new RNA chain snaps into place.",
      "title": "First Nucleotide Locks On"
    },
    {
      "text": "Now the machine moves forward, one base at a time. Read, match, attach. Read, match, attach. RNA polymerase slides along the template strand like a zipper pull, leaving a growing RNA tail trailing behind it.",
      "title": "The Chain Grows Base by Base"
    },
    {
      "text": "As RNA polymerase advances, something elegant happens behind it — the DNA strands immediately zip back together. The helix reforms automatically, like a self-healing zipper. Only a small 'bubble' of separation exists at any moment.",
      "title": "DNA Rezips Behind"
    },
    {
      "text": "The fresh RNA strand doesn't cling to the DNA. As it's built, it peels away from the template, dangling free. This single-stranded messenger begins to coil and fold, preparing for its journey out of the nucleus.",
      "title": "The RNA Strand Peels Away"
    },
    {
      "text": "RNA polymerase eventually hits a terminator sequence — DNA's way of saying 'stop here.' The machine releases its grip on both the DNA and the newly minted RNA strand. Transcription is complete.",
      "title": "The Stop Signal Hits"
    },
    {
      "text": "The finished messenger RNA drifts away from the DNA, carrying its copied genetic instructions. Meanwhile, RNA polymerase detaches completely, ready to find another promoter and start the whole process again.",
      "title": "Message Released, Machine Resets"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "You type a URL and press Enter. Your browser springs into action, first parsing that address to extract the protocol, domain, and path — like reading an envelope to know where to send your letter.",
      "title": "The Journey Begins"
    },
    {
      "text": "Before anything can travel, your browser asks DNS: \"Where does this domain live?\" DNS responds with an IP address — the actual street address of the server you're trying to reach.",
      "title": "Finding the Server's Address"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your browser now opens a TCP connection to that IP address. Think of it as establishing a phone line — both sides agree they can hear each other before the real conversation starts.",
      "title": "Establishing the Connection"
    },
    {
      "text": "For HTTPS sites, a security handshake happens next. Your browser and the server exchange encryption keys, creating a private tunnel. Now eavesdroppers can't read what flows between you.",
      "title": "The TLS Handshake"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your browser constructs the HTTP request — method, path, headers, maybe a body. It's like filling out a detailed form: what you want, who you are, what format you prefer.",
      "title": "Building the Request"
    },
    {
      "text": "The request travels through routers and networks, hopping between machines until it reaches the destination server. Each hop brings your message closer to its target.",
      "title": "Across the Network"
    },
    {
      "text": "The server receives your request and starts processing. It reads the method to understand your intent, checks headers for context, and routes everything to the right handler.",
      "title": "Server Receives and Parses"
    },
    {
      "text": "The server does its work — querying databases, running logic, fetching files. This is where your request transforms into something useful, like a kitchen preparing your order.",
      "title": "Processing the Request"
    },
    {
      "text": "The server packages its response: a status code summarizing the outcome, headers with metadata, and a body containing the actual content you requested.",
      "title": "Crafting the Response"
    },
    {
      "text": "The response travels back through the network, retracing the path to your browser. The TCP connection ensures every piece arrives intact and in order.",
      "title": "The Return Trip"
    },
    {
      "text": "Your browser receives the response and checks the status code first. Success? It proceeds. Error? It handles accordingly. The code tells the browser what happened in one glance.",
      "title": "Browser Reads the Status"
    },
    {
      "text": "For HTML responses, the browser begins parsing immediately. It discovers images, scripts, and stylesheets — each triggering NEW HTTP requests. One page can spawn dozens of cycles.",
      "title": "Parsing Triggers More Requests"
    },
    {
      "text": "Finally, all resources arrive and the page renders on your screen. What felt instant was actually a rapid sequence of connections, requests, responses, and parsing — all in milliseconds.",
      "title": "The Page Appears"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Your program creates an object — maybe a new user session. The runtime allocates space on the heap and hands back a reference. That reference gets stored somewhere: a variable, a list, a field. The object is now \"alive\" because something points to it.",
      "title": "An Object Is Born"
    },
    {
      "text": "As your code runs, references shift constantly. A variable gets reassigned. A function returns and its local references vanish. A list gets cleared. Each change potentially cuts the lifeline to some object sitting on the heap.",
      "title": "References Shift and Break"
    },
    {
      "text": "At some point — maybe memory is running low, maybe a threshold was hit — the garbage collector wakes up. It's like a detective asking: \"Which objects are still needed?\" Time to trace the evidence.",
      "title": "The Collector Awakens"
    },
    {
      "text": "The GC starts at the roots and asks, \"What can I reach from here?\" It follows each reference like pulling on a thread. Object A points to Object B, which points to Object C. All three get marked as reachable — they're survivors.",
      "title": "Tracing From the Roots"
    },
    {
      "text": "The collector keeps following references, building a map of everything connected to the roots. Think of it like exploring a maze — every path gets walked, every room gets visited. Anything touched is marked \"alive.\"",
      "title": "The Marking Phase"
    },
    {
      "text": "Once marking finishes, the collector knows exactly who survived. Any object NOT marked? It's unreachable. No path from any root leads to it. It's been forgotten by your program — a ghost occupying valuable memory.",
      "title": "Unreachable Objects Exposed"
    },
    {
      "text": "Now comes cleanup. The collector reclaims memory from unmarked objects. That space returns to the free pool, ready for new allocations. The ghosts are evicted; the heap has room to breathe again.",
      "title": "Reclaiming Dead Memory"
    },
    {
      "text": "After sweeping, the heap can look like Swiss cheese — free space scattered between live objects. Some collectors compact memory, sliding survivors together. This creates contiguous free space and improves allocation speed.",
      "title": "Compacting the Survivors"
    },
    {
      "text": "Collection isn't free. While the GC traces and sweeps, your program might pause — nothing else can safely move memory around while you're using it. This \"stop-the-world\" moment is the price of automatic cleanup.",
      "title": "The Pause Tax"
    },
    {
      "text": "Modern collectors get clever. They might run concurrently, tracing while your code executes. Or they divide the heap into generations — young objects die fast, old ones rarely do. Each trick minimizes disruption.",
      "title": "Optimizing the Hunt"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Imagine um fóton de luz viajando do Sol até uma folha. No instante em que ele atinge a clorofila no Fotossistema II, um elétron é arrancado — como uma mola sendo solta. O processo começa.",
      "title": "A Luz Chega e Dispara Tudo"
    },
    {
      "text": "O elétron perdido deixa um \"buraco\" na clorofila. Para preencher essa lacuna, o Fotossistema II quebra uma molécula de água. Ela se parte em oxigênio, prótons e elétrons — é daí que vem o O₂ que respiramos.",
      "title": "Água Se Quebra Para Repor"
    },
    {
      "text": "O elétron energizado não fica parado. Ele pula de proteína em proteína na cadeia transportadora de elétrons, como uma bola descendo escadas. A cada salto, libera energia.",
      "title": "Elétrons Descem a Escada"
    },
    {
      "text": "Essa energia liberada não se perde. Ela é usada para bombear prótons (H⁺) para dentro do tilacoide. Os prótons se acumulam como água atrás de uma represa — criando pressão.",
      "title": "Bombeamento Cria Pressão"
    },
    {
      "text": "O elétron, já com menos energia, chega ao Fotossistema I. Ali, outro fóton de luz o recarrega — dando um novo impulso de energia para continuar a jornada.",
      "title": "Fotossistema I Recarrega"
    },
    {
      "text": "Com energia renovada, o elétron segue para seu destino final: a ferredoxina e depois a enzima NADP redutase. Ali, ele se une a prótons e NADP⁺ para formar NADPH.",
      "title": "NADPH É Montado"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lembra dos prótons acumulados? Eles só têm uma saída: a ATP sintase. Ao passarem por ela como água por turbina, fazem a enzima girar — literalmente. Cada volta produz ATP.",
      "title": "A Turbina Gira e Faz ATP"
    },
    {
      "text": "Agora o ciclo se fecha. ATP e NADPH estão prontos, carregados de energia. Eles seguem para o estroma, onde alimentarão as reações escuras — mas essa já é outra história.",
      "title": "Energia Pronta Para a Fase Seguinte"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Imagina una subasta de pescado al amanecer. Los pescadores llegan con sus capturas, los compradores con sus billeteras. Nadie ha puesto un precio todavía — el descubrimiento está por comenzar.",
      "title": "El mercado abre sus puertas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Un vendedor lanza el primer número: \"¡Atún a 50 pesos el kilo!\" Es solo una propuesta, un globo de prueba. Observa las caras de los compradores buscando señales de interés o rechazo.",
      "title": "Alguien propone un precio"
    },
    {
      "text": "Los compradores responden con sus acciones. Algunos se acercan interesados, otros se alejan murmurando que está caro. Cada reacción envía información valiosa de vuelta al vendedor.",
      "title": "El mercado responde"
    },
    {
      "text": "El vendedor nota pocas ventas y ajusta: \"¡Ahora a 45!\" Como un termostato que detecta temperatura, el precio se mueve respondiendo a las señales del mercado.",
      "title": "El precio se ajusta"
    },
    {
      "text": "Simultáneamente, otros vendedores observan y ajustan sus propios precios. Es como una conversación donde todos escuchan a todos — cada movimiento influye en los demás.",
      "title": "La información se propaga"
    },
    {
      "text": "Con el precio más bajo, más compradores se interesan. Pero si baja demasiado, algunos vendedores prefieren guardar su pescado para mañana. El tira y afloja continúa.",
      "title": "Compradores y vendedores negocian"
    },
    {
      "text": "Gradualmente, los ajustes se vuelven más pequeños. El precio oscila menos. Como agua encontrando su nivel, el mercado se acerca a un punto donde nadie tiene incentivo para cambiar.",
      "title": "Las oscilaciones se calman"
    },
    {
      "text": "A 42 pesos, algo mágico ocurre: cada kilo que los vendedores quieren vender encuentra un comprador dispuesto. Las colas desaparecen, los excedentes también. El precio de equilibrio emergió.",
      "title": "El equilibrio emerge"
    },
    {
      "text": "Este precio no lo decidió ninguna autoridad. Surgió de miles de pequeñas decisiones individuales, cada una buscando su propio beneficio pero coordinándose sin saberlo.",
      "title": "Nadie lo planeó"
    },
    {
      "text": "Si mañana llegan menos pescadores por una tormenta, el proceso reinicia. Menos oferta, misma demanda — observa cómo el precio sube hasta que el mercado vuelve a equilibrarse.",
      "title": "El proceso nunca termina"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "A Neutron Finds Its Target",
      "title": "A Neutron Finds Its Target"
    },
    {
      "text": "Picture a slow neutron drifting through a chunk of uranium-235. It collides with a nucleus and gets absorbed. The nucleus wobbles violently, suddenly unstable — like a water droplet stretched too far. Within a trillionth of a second, it tears apart.",
      "title": "A Neutron Finds Its Target"
    },
    {
      "text": "As the nucleus splits, it doesn't just release energy — it ejects two or three fresh neutrons. These new neutrons fly outward in random directions at tremendous speed, each one a potential trigger for another fission event.",
      "title": "The Split Releases More Neutrons"
    },
    {
      "text": "Here's where chain reactions live or die. Those ejected neutrons need to find more U-235 nuclei to continue the process. If they escape the material or hit non-fissile atoms, the chain breaks. If they find targets, it multiplies.",
      "title": "The Critical Question"
    },
    {
      "text": "Imagine one fission produces two neutrons that each cause another fission. Now you have four, then eight, then sixteen. Each generation doubles in microseconds. This exponential growth is what makes nuclear reactions so extraordinarily powerful.",
      "title": "Multiplication Takes Off"
    },
    {
      "text": "For this multiplication to sustain itself, you need enough fissile material packed closely enough. This threshold is called critical mass. Below it, too many neutrons escape before finding targets. The reaction fizzles out like a wet firecracker.",
      "title": "Critical Mass Sets the Stage"
    },
    {
      "text": "Reach critical mass and suddenly more neutrons cause fissions than escape. The reaction becomes self-sustaining — each generation produces at least one successful hit. Cross into supercritical territory and it grows explosively with each cycle.",
      "title": "Going Critical"
    },
    {
      "text": "In a reactor, control rods made of neutron-absorbing materials slide between fuel assemblies. Push them in, and they capture neutrons before they can trigger fissions. Pull them out, and more neutrons find uranium targets. It's like adjusting a gas pedal.",
      "title": "Control Rods Join the Dance"
    },
    {
      "text": "Some fission products release neutrons slightly after the split — delayed neutrons. These slower arrivals give operators precious seconds to adjust controls. Without them, reactors would respond too fast for human control.",
      "title": "Delayed Neutrons Buy Time"
    },
    {
      "text": "In a bomb, there are no control rods. Two subcritical masses slam together, instantly exceeding critical mass. The chain reaction multiplies through dozens of generations in microseconds, releasing city-destroying energy before the material can fly apart.",
      "title": "Runaway: No Brakes"
    },
    {
      "text": "The chain ends when fissile material spreads too thin, neutrons escape faster than they multiply, or control rods absorb enough to break the cycle. Every chain reaction is a race between multiplication and loss — controlled or catastrophic depends on who wins.",
      "title": "How the Chain Breaks"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Picture a coil of wire sitting peacefully in space. A magnet rests nearby, its invisible field lines passing through the coil's loops. Nothing moves, nothing happens — the electrons in the wire stay put, waiting.",
      "title": "The Calm Before the Storm"
    },
    {
      "text": "Now push the magnet toward the coil. Watch closely — as the magnet approaches, more field lines thread through the wire loops. The magnetic flux through the coil is climbing, and the electrons sense this change.",
      "title": "The Magnet Starts Moving"
    },
    {
      "text": "Here's where the magic happens: those electrons don't like change. As flux increases, they feel a push — a force that shoves them along the wire. Current starts flowing, born purely from motion and magnetism.",
      "title": "Electrons Feel the Push"
    },
    {
      "text": "The faster you move the magnet, the more dramatically the flux changes. Electrons respond with urgency — more current flows, higher voltage appears. Speed is everything in this process.",
      "title": "Speed Amplifies the Effect"
    },
    {
      "text": "Try the reverse: pull the magnet away. The flux through the coil drops, and electrons get pushed the opposite direction. The current reverses! The wire doesn't care which way flux changes — just THAT it changes.",
      "title": "Reverse Creates Reverse"
    },
    {
      "text": "Now stop the magnet completely. Even with it inside the coil, if nothing moves, flux stays constant. The electrons relax, current dies. No change means no induction — motion is the essential ingredient.",
      "title": "Stop and the Current Dies"
    },
    {
      "text": "This works both ways. Keep the magnet still and move the coil instead. The electrons can't tell the difference — all they sense is flux changing through their wire home. Same result, different mover.",
      "title": "Move the Coil Instead"
    },
    {
      "text": "Generators exploit this dance continuously. Spinning coils cut through magnetic fields, flux rises and falls rhythmically. Electrons surge back and forth, creating the alternating current that powers your world.",
      "title": "Generators Spin This Dance"
    },
    {
      "text": "What if the magnetic field changes without physical motion? Flip an electromagnet's strength up and down, and the nearby coil experiences changing flux. Current flows in response — this is how transformers work.",
      "title": "No Motion? Change the Field"
    },
    {
      "text": "The induced current creates its own magnetic field. Nature resists the original change — push a magnet in, and the coil's field pushes back. This opposition is why you feel resistance when moving magnets near conductors.",
      "title": "The Coil Fights Back"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Imagine uma molécula de substrato flutuando no ambiente celular. Ela se aproxima da enzima e reconhece o sítio ativo — como uma chave encontrando sua fechadura. A reação está prestes a começar.",
      "title": "O Substrato Encontra sua Enzima"
    },
    {
      "text": "O substrato encaixa no sítio ativo e algo interessante acontece: a enzima se ajusta levemente ao redor dele. Não é um encaixe rígido — é como uma luva que se molda à mão, abraçando o substrato com precisão.",
      "title": "O Encaixe Induzido"
    },
    {
      "text": "Com o substrato preso, aminoácidos do sítio ativo entram em ação. Alguns doam prótons, outros os retiram. Essas interações químicas começam a esticar e enfraquecer ligações específicas do substrato.",
      "title": "Forças Químicas em Movimento"
    },
    {
      "text": "A enzima força o substrato a assumir uma forma instável — o estado de transição. É como dobrar um galho até quase quebrar. Nesse momento tenso, a reação está no ponto de virada.",
      "title": "O Estado de Transição"
    },
    {
      "text": "As ligações enfraquecidas se rompem. Novas ligações se formam. A transformação química acontece em frações de segundo — o que levaria anos sem enzima ocorre instantaneamente com ela.",
      "title": "A Transformação Acontece"
    },
    {
      "text": "O produto recém-formado não encaixa mais tão bem no sítio ativo. A afinidade diminui e ele se solta naturalmente, liberando espaço para o próximo substrato que já se aproxima.",
      "title": "Produto Liberado"
    },
    {
      "text": "A enzima permanece intacta após a reação. Ela não foi consumida — apenas facilitou o processo. Agora está pronta para receber outro substrato e repetir o ciclo milhares de vezes por segundo.",
      "title": "Ciclo Reinicia"
    },
    {
      "text": "Se a temperatura sobe demais ou o pH muda drasticamente, a enzima perde sua forma tridimensional. O sítio ativo se deforma e o substrato não encaixa mais — a catálise para completamente.",
      "title": "Quando o Sistema Falha"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Todo comienza cuando conectas la fuente de poder. La corriente eléctrica empieza a fluir hacia los electrodos, creando una diferencia de potencial que obligará a los iones a moverse contra su voluntad natural.",
      "title": "Se enciende la corriente"
    },
    {
      "text": "Los cationes en solución sienten la atracción del cátodo negativo. Es como un imán invisible: las cargas positivas no pueden resistirse y comienzan a migrar hacia el electrodo negativo.",
      "title": "Los cationes se ponen en marcha"
    },
    {
      "text": "Simultáneamente, los aniones negativos son atraídos hacia el ánodo positivo. La solución se convierte en un río de tráfico iónico, con partículas moviéndose en direcciones opuestas.",
      "title": "Los aniones viajan al ánodo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Al llegar al cátodo, los cationes reciben electrones del circuito externo. Observa cómo un ion metálico captura electrones y se transforma: de partícula cargada a átomo neutro. Esto es reducción en acción.",
      "title": "Reducción en el cátodo"
    },
    {
      "text": "En el ánodo ocurre lo contrario. Los aniones ceden sus electrones al electrodo. Un ion cloruro, por ejemplo, libera su electrón extra y se convierte en cloro gaseoso. Esto es oxidación.",
      "title": "Oxidación en el ánodo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Los electrones cedidos en el ánodo no desaparecen. Viajan por el cable conductor hacia la fuente de poder, que los empuja de regreso al cátodo. El circuito se cierra y el flujo continúa.",
      "title": "El circuito se completa"
    },
    {
      "text": "La energía eléctrica que introduces fuerza una reacción que nunca ocurriría sola. Es como empujar agua cuesta arriba: sin tu energía externa, los productos nunca se formarían espontáneamente.",
      "title": "Energía que vence la termodinámica"
    },
    {
      "text": "Con el tiempo, el cátodo puede cubrirse de metal depositado mientras burbujas de gas escapan del ánodo. Los productos de la electrólisis se acumulan, visibles y separados en cada electrodo.",
      "title": "Los productos aparecen"
    },
    {
      "text": "Si la corriente es muy débil, la reacción avanza lentamente. Si el voltaje es insuficiente, la reacción ni siquiera arranca. La electrólisis exige superar un umbral mínimo de energía para funcionar.",
      "title": "Cuando el proceso se detiene"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "The central bank announces a rate change. Within minutes, traders across global markets react. This single decision will ripple through millions of transactions over the coming months.",
      "title": "The Announcement Drops"
    },
    {
      "text": "Commercial banks immediately adjust what they charge each other for overnight loans. The policy rate acts like a peg — all other rates shift to maintain their usual distance from it.",
      "title": "Interbank Rates Shift First"
    },
    {
      "text": "Banks recalculate their lending rates. A lower policy rate means cheaper funding, so they can offer cheaper mortgages and business loans. Higher rates trigger the opposite cascade.",
      "title": "Lending Rates Follow"
    },
    {
      "text": "Companies run the numbers on expansion plans. That factory project that didn't make sense at 7% suddenly works at 5%. Investment decisions flip from 'no' to 'yes' across thousands of boardrooms.",
      "title": "Businesses Recalculate"
    },
    {
      "text": "Households feel the shift through their wallets. Lower mortgage rates mean bigger homes become affordable. Credit card rates drop, making that renovation more tempting.",
      "title": "Households Respond"
    },
    {
      "text": "As borrowing costs fall, spending increases. Factories hire more workers to meet demand. Those workers spend their paychecks, creating even more demand — the multiplier effect kicks in.",
      "title": "Spending Multiplies"
    },
    {
      "text": "With more money chasing goods, businesses test higher prices. If demand stays strong, inflation starts climbing. The policy change has finally reached the price level.",
      "title": "Prices Start Moving"
    },
    {
      "text": "The full journey from rate announcement to inflation impact takes 12-18 months. Central bankers must act on forecasts, not current conditions — like steering a ship by where it will be, not where it is.",
